# Auth + Canvas Management

## Plan

- NextAuth with Google OAuth
- User table + associate canvases to users
- Left sidebar: list of user's canvases, create new, rename, delete
- Canvas switcher — clicking a canvas in sidebar loads it
- Default canvas name: "Untitled Canvas" (click to rename inline)
- Redirect unauthenticated users to sign-in page
- Sign-out button

## Acceptance

- Sign in with Google works, session persists
- Each user only sees their own canvases
- Create new canvas → appears in sidebar → loads blank canvas
- Rename canvas inline in sidebar
- Delete canvas (with confirmation) removes it and all nodes/edges
- Switching canvases loads correct state
- Sign-out clears session, redirects to sign-in

## Built

### Auth
- NextAuth v5 with Google OAuth provider
- User upsert on sign-in (insert if not exists, keyed by email)
- JWT stores `dbUserId`, session exposes it as `session.user.id`
- `src/types/next-auth.d.ts` augments session and JWT types
- Middleware protects `/canvas/*`, redirects unauthenticated users to `/`
- Post-signin route redirects to most recent canvas or creates a new one
- All API routes (`/api/nodes`, `/api/edges`, `/api/canvases`) return 401 if no session, 403 if wrong user

### Landing page
- Obsidian-inspired dark design
- Hero: headline, subheadline, "Sign in with Google" CTA
- 6-card features grid: The Canvas, Node Editing, Keyboard-First, Subtree Actions, Session Colors, Heading Hierarchy
- Server component — redirects authenticated users directly to their canvas

### Canvas management
- `Sidebar.tsx`: canvas list sorted by `updatedAt DESC`, new canvas button, sign-out
- `SidebarItem.tsx`: double-click to rename inline, single-confirm delete
- `canvases` schema: `userId` FK added and migration applied to Neon

### Collapsible sidebar
- Framer Motion animates width `0 ↔ 260px` on toggle
- `SidebarToggle.tsx`: fixed top-left button with document icon SVG
- `SidebarContext.tsx`: `isOpen` + `toggle` in React context, persisted to `localStorage` (`jewel-sidebar-open`)
- `src/app/canvas/layout.tsx`: wraps all canvas routes in `SidebarProvider` so state survives canvas switches

### Stable canvas switching
- Removed full-page loading spinner; loading state now scoped to canvas area only
- Sidebar stays mounted during canvas loads — no remount, no flicker
- `Sidebar` reads `currentCanvasId` from `usePathname()` instead of a prop, eliminating refetch and item flicker on navigation